<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[376,631,188,214]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[376,631,188,214]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Maryvillia bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, respectively, are from the same collection, and he considered them to represent a single species under the former name. The cranidium of 
<taxonomicName authority="Resser (1938)" authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[916,1313,224,251]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[916,1149,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Blountia bristolensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Resser, C. E." box="[1157,1313,225,251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 140" refId="ref23917" refString="Resser, C. E. (1938) The Cambrian (Restricted) of the southern Appalachians. Geological Society of America Special Papers, 15, 1 - 140." type="journal article" year="1938">Resser (1938)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has a relatively short frontal area that occupies 25% (23–26) of cranidial length, and with a preglabellar field that varies from slightly longer to slightly shorter than the anterior border. There is an abrupt change in slope at border furrow. An exoskeleton assigned to the species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasetti, F." box="[580,738,332,359]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 127" refId="ref23892" refString="Rasetti, F. (1965) Upper Cambrian trilobite faunas of Northeastern Tennessee. Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections, 148, 1 - 127." type="journal article" year="1965">Rasetti (1965)</bibRefCitation>
(Pl. 3, figs 3–7) has similar frontal area proportions to Resser’s cranidia and appears to be conspecific.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Both 
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, A. R." box="[260,420,404,431]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref23721" refString="Palmer, A. R. (1965) Trilobites of the Late Cambrian Pterocephaliid Biomere in the Great Basin, United States. U. S. Geological Survey Professional Paper, 463, 1 - 105. https: // doi. org / 10.3133 / pp 493" type="journal article" year="1965">Palmer (1965)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasetti, F." box="[473,632,404,431]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 127" refId="ref23892" refString="Rasetti, F. (1965) Upper Cambrian trilobite faunas of Northeastern Tennessee. Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections, 148, 1 - 127." type="journal article" year="1965">Rasetti (1965)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName authority="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan, 1944" authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[766,1436,404,431]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nixonensis">
<emphasis box="[766,986,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Blountia nixonensis</emphasis>
Lochman, in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D." box="[1140,1436,404,431]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref23573" refString="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D. (1944) Early Upper Cambrian faunas of Central Montana. Geological Society of America Special Papers, 54, 1 - 172. https: // doi. org / 10.1130 / SPE 54 - p 1" type="journal article" year="1944">Lochman &amp; Duncan, 1944</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[415,650,440,466]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[415,650,440,466]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Blountia bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D." box="[925,1237,440,467]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref23573" refString="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D. (1944) Early Upper Cambrian faunas of Central Montana. Geological Society of America Special Papers, 54, 1 - 172. https: // doi. org / 10.1130 / SPE 54 - p 1" type="journal article" year="1944">Lochman &amp; Duncan (1944</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 4, figs 7–12) could not be located at the USNM, but their previously unillustrated 
<typeStatus box="[943,1050,477,503]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">paratypes</typeStatus>
(Pls 4, 5) are closely comparable to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[181,341,512,539]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[181,198,513,538]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[212,341,512,538]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and we agree that they belong to the same species. However, sclerites from the Mendha Formation in 
<collectingRegion box="[231,317,548,574]" country="United States of America" name="Nevada" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Nevada</collectingRegion>
that 
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, A. R." box="[374,528,548,575]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref23721" refString="Palmer, A. R. (1965) Trilobites of the Late Cambrian Pterocephaliid Biomere in the Great Basin, United States. U. S. Geological Survey Professional Paper, 463, 1 - 105. https: // doi. org / 10.3133 / pp 493" type="journal article" year="1965">Palmer (1965</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 1, figs 2–3) identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[859,1092,548,574]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[859,1092,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Blountia bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are assigned to a new species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westrop &amp; Eoff" authorityYear="2020" box="[151,378,584,610]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nevadensis">
<emphasis box="[151,378,584,610]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Blountia nevadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pl. 16). Cranidia of the latter (Pl. 16, figs 1–3, 8) differ clearly in having a longer frontal area that features a nasute border that narrows abaxially. The pygidium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westrop &amp; Eoff" authorityYear="2020" box="[943,1099,620,647]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nevadensis">
<emphasis box="[943,960,621,646]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[976,1099,620,646]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">nevadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively narrower (length equal to 69% of maximum width, versus 55% in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[700,860,656,683]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[700,717,657,682]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[731,860,656,682]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Cranidia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Westrop &amp; Eoff, 2020" authorityName="Westrop &amp; Eoff" authorityYear="2020" box="[334,581,692,718]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="newfoundlandensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[334,581,692,718]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B. newfoundlandensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[588,651,693,719]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[588,651,693,719]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(Pl. 13, figs 5–10, Pl. 20, Pl. 21) from the Cow Head Group, western Newfoundland, resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[455,617,728,755]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[455,472,729,754]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[488,617,728,754]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in possessing a relatively short frontal area. The former species differs by having a narrower glabella (glabellar width is 69% of length versus 79% in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[1040,1201,764,791]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[1040,1057,765,790]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1072,1201,764,790]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and palpebral lobes situated slightly farther forward. Pygidial differences are decisive in separating these species. The pygidium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westrop &amp; Eoff" authorityYear="2020" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="newfoundlandensis">
<emphasis box="[1412,1429,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,366,836,862]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">newfoundlandensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pl. 21) displays a border that expands noticeably towards the axis to occupy18% of pygidial length (sag.) In contrast, the border of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Resser" authorityYear="1938" box="[583,743,872,899]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bristolensis">
<emphasis box="[583,600,873,898]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[614,743,872,898]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">bristolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
maintains a nearly even width along the pygidial margin, and is relatively shorter, accounting for 10% (8–12) of pygidial length (sag.).
</paragraph>
